        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Method"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Caramelize the onions: Heat the olive oil in a large skillet or pot over medium heat. Add the sliced onions and cook, stirring occasionally, for about 15–20 minutes. Lower the heat as the onions soften and turn golden brown. Stir occasionally to ensure they don't burn. The slow cooking process will bring out the natural sweetness of the onions. Once caramelized, remove the onions from the skillet and set them aside."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Cook the bacon: In the same skillet, add the chopped bacon and cook over medium heat until crispy, about 5–7 minutes. Remove the bacon with a slotted spoon and set aside on a paper towel-lined plate to drain any excess fat."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Prepare the risotto: In the same skillet, add the Arborio rice and toast it for 1–2 minutes, stirring to coat the rice in the bacon fat. Slowly add the white wine (if using), stirring constantly until most of the liquid is absorbed by the rice. Begin adding the chicken broth, one ladleful at a time, stirring frequently and allowing each addition to be absorbed before adding the next. Continue this process until the rice is creamy and al dente, about 20–25 minutes. You may not need all the broth, so keep tasting and checking the texture of the rice as you go."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Finish the risotto: Once the rice is cooked to your liking, stir in the caramelized onions, crispy bacon, butter, and grated Parmesan cheese. Mix until everything is well combined, and the cheese and butter have melted into the risotto. Season with salt and pepper to taste."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Serve: Spoon the risotto onto plates and garnish with extra Parmesan and fresh parsley if desired. Serve hot!"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
